english:
  title: In Praise of the Sixteen-Foot Vairocana Buddha Statue
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The monk Hakju has cast a sixteen-foot statue of Vairocana Buddha for the main hall of Hyangsan Temple, and asked me to compose an inscription. I bow before the sacred image and humbly offer this praise:

    Vairocana the Great Sage, your body pure and crystalline—
    Yet what measure holds your length? I cannot say.
    Would you fashion this in sixteen feet?
    With what rule could one ever measure you?

    When I open my eyes wide to gaze upon you,
    You grow ever more subtle and mysterious,
    Beyond compare to the finest hair or mayfly—
    Yet closing my eyes to perceive your true form,
    You expand so vast that heaven and earth,
    The six directions themselves, seem but small.

    If one dared calculate in feet and measure in lengths,
    The stone maiden and wooden boy would clap their hands and laugh.
  footnotes:
    - Vairocana (Biroluja) is the primordial Buddha representing ultimate reality in Mahayana Buddhism, often depicted as transcending all physical dimensions.
    - The sixteen-foot measurement refers to a specific sculptural tradition in East Asian Buddhism, representing an idealized proportion.
    - The 'stone maiden and wooden boy' are figures from Daoist and Buddhist paradoxical teaching, used here to mock the futility of measuring the immeasurable with human standards.
